The state of being satiated or glutted; fullness ofgratification, either of the appetite or of any sensual desire;fullness beyond desire; an excess of gratification which exciteswearisomeness or loathing; repletion; satiation.In all pleasures there is satiety. Hakewill.But thy words, with grace divine Imbued, bring to their sweetness nosatiety. Milton.

To bear fruit. "Causeth the earth to fructify." Beveridge.

Not embarrassed. Specifically: --(a) Not perplexed in mind; not confused; as, the speaker appearedunembarrassed.(b) Free from pecuniary difficulties or encumbrances; as, he and hisproperty are unembarrassed.(c) Free from perplexing connection; as, the question comes intocourt unembarrassed with irrelevant matter.
